metaData.descriptionCS: The examinee hears each letter sound within the context of a word, and each word within the context of a sentence, and then the student writes the target letter sound or word.

data.message:
For Grades K-1 only: Give the examinee a pencil without an eraser and say, You will be using a pencil without an eraser, so if you make a mistake, just cross it out. Open the Response Booklet to Spelling Item 1 and hand it to the examinee. Say, 1. I am going to ask you to write some letters and words.

Grades K-12+: Say, Next to number 1 (point to the appropriate line), please write your first name.

If examinee does not respond, encourage him or her to write as much as he or she can.

scoreButtons.label: Examinee's first name spelled correctly, disregard capitalization

data.message: Say, 2. Write the letter that makes the \a\ sound in apple.
Say, 3. Write the letter that makes the \z\ sound in zoo.
Say, 4. Write the letter that makes the \j\ sound in jump.
Say, 5. Write the letter that makes the \k\ sound in kite.

For Grades K-1 only: Say, Now let’s try writing some words. I will say a word, then use it in a sentence, and say the word again. Listen to the sentence so you know what word to write. 

Grades K-12: Say, 6. Cat. The cat is chasing a mouse. Cat.

For Grade 2 only: Give the examinee a pencil without an eraser and say, You will be using a pencil without an eraser, so if you make a mistake, just cross it out. Open the Response Booklet to Spelling Item 7 and hand it to the examinee. Say, I want you to write some words. I will say a word, then use it in a sentence, and say the word again. Listen to the sentence so you know what word to write.

Grades K-12+: Say, 7. In. My books are in my room. In.
Say, 8. Be. Be careful. Be.

For Grade 3 only: Give the examinee a pencil without an eraser and say, You will be using a pencil without an eraser, so if you make a mistake, just cross it out. Open the Response Booklet to Spelling Item 9 and hand it to the examinee. Say, I want you to write some words. I will say a word, then use it in a sentence, and say the word again. Listen to the sentence so you know what word to write.

Grades K-12+: Say, 9. Game. The children played a game outside. Game.
Say, 10. Fix. She used tape to fix the book. Fix.
Say, 11. Cake. I had cake for dessert. Cake.
Say, 12. Cold. It is cold outside. Cold.
Say, 13. Tall. The bird made a nest in a tall tree. Tall.
Say, 14. Mother. The child asked his mother for a cookie. Mother.
Say, 15. Night. The stars can be seen at night. Night.

For Grades 4-8 only: Give the examinee a pencil without an eraser and say, You will be using a pencil without an eraser, so if you make a mistake, just cross it out. Open the Response Booklet to Spelling Item 16 and hand it to the examinee. Say, I want you to write some words. I will say a word, then use it in a sentence, and say the word again. Listen to the sentence so you know what word to write.

Grades K-12+: Say, 16. Page. The book was missing a page. Page.
Say, 17. Began. Class began five minutes late. Began.
Say, 18. Windy. On windy days, the leaves blow through the air. Windy.
Say, 19. Camped. We camped in the forest and slept in a tent. Camped.

For Grades 9-12+ only: Give the examinee a pencil without an eraser and say, You will be using a pencil without an eraser, so if you make a mistake, just cross it out. Open the Response Booklet to Spelling Item 20 and hand it to the examinee. Say, I want you to write some words. I will say a word, then use it in a sentence, and say the word again. Listen to the sentence so you know what word to write.

Grades K-12+: Say, 20. Suspect. The suspect was arrested at the bank. Suspect.
Say, 21. Inactive. People are usually inactive while watching television. Inactive.
Say, 22. Known. The author was known throughout the world. Known.
Say, 23. Happily. The characters lived happily ever after. Happily.
Say, 24. Stationary. Stationary objects do not move. Stationary.
Say, 25. Collection. I have a collection of coins. Collection.
Say, 26. Budget. A budget helps to organize finances. Budget.
Say, 27. Width. The width of the door was too narrow for the box to fit through. Width.
Say, 28. Guitar. I am learning how to play the guitar. Guitar.
Say, 29. Photography. Photography is a hobby of mine. Photography.
Say, 30. Factual. A factual statement is true. Factual.
Say, 31. Resign. I want to resign and start a new job. Resign.
Say, 32. Doubt. I doubt it will rain today because the sky is clear. Doubt.
Say, 33. Progressive. Progressive research uses new ideas to make advances. Progressive.
Say, 34. Suppose. I studied for the test, so I suppose I’ll do well. Suppose.
Say, 35. Confide. I will confide in you if you will keep a secret. Confide.
Say, 36. Resistance. A healthy diet may improve our resistance to illness. Resistance.
Say, 37. Exerting. I opened the heavy door by exerting pressure. Exerting.
Say, 38. Presence. The dog barks in the presence of a stranger. Presence.
Say, 39. Reign. The queen would reign for fifty years. Reign.
Say, 40. Ambitious. To become a world leader is an ambitious goal. Ambitious.
Say, 41. Outrageous. The announcer’s outrageous comments made the crowd laugh. Outrageous.
Say, 42. Sympathetic. I felt sympathetic towards the crying baby. Sympathetic.
Say, 43. Leisure. In my leisure time, I enjoy watching movies. Leisure.
Say, 44. Oxidize. Oxygen causes copper to oxidize. Oxidize.
Say, 45. Achievement. Graduating from high school is an important achievement. Achievement.
Say, 46. Absurd. It is absurd to think you can get water out of a stone. Absurd.
Say, 47. Kindliness. I try to practice kindliness with everyone I meet. Kindliness.
Say, 48. Metabolize. Exercise helps our bodies metabolize food. Metabolize.
Say, 49. Exhaustion. The runner collapsed from exhaustion after the marathon. Exhaustion.
Say, 50. Affluent. Many people cannot afford to live in an affluent neighborhood. Affluent.
Say, 51. Flirtatious. The male peacock showed off his feathers in a flirtatious manner. Flirtatious.
Say, 52. Stasis. During a time of stasis, little or no change occurs. Stasis.
Say, 53. Receiving. My teacher enjoys receiving letters from students. Receiving.
Say, 54. Heterodox. Heterodox beliefs do not agree with traditional beliefs. Heterodox.
Say, 55. Vacuum. I vacuum the rug once a week. Vacuum.
Say, 56. Conferred. I conferred with my lawyer before making a decision. Conferred.
Say, 57. Physicist. A physicist studies the natural world. Physicist.
Say, 58. Recede. I waited for the tide to recede before looking for seashells. Recede.
Say, 59. Perceived. The audience perceived the nervousness in the speaker’s voice. Perceived.
Say, 60. Abhors. My friend abhors insects and avoids them at all cost. Abhors.
Say, 61. Marionette. There was a dancing marionette in the talent show. Marionette.
Say, 62. Impeccable. After studying for many years, the student speaks impeccable French. Impeccable.
Say, 63. Gherkin. A gherkin is a young, pickled cucumber. Gherkin.
